==Biography== Norio Hayakawa is from Yokohama, Japan, but calls [[New Mexico]] his home. He attended [[Spanish language|Spanish]] classes at the [[University of New Mexico]], and graduated in 1970.<ref>{{cite book |last=Sanchez|first1=Anthony F. |url=http://www.ufohighway.com |title=UFO HIGHWAY: The Dulce Interview, Human Origins, HAARP |chapter=FOREWORD "By Norio F. Hayakawa" |accessdate=October 1, 2011 }}</ref><ref name="Rojas 2014">{{cite web|last=Rojas|first=Alejandro|title=Norio Hayakawa - UFOs in New Mexico - September 29, 2014|website=Openminds.tv|date=September 29, 2014|url=http://www.openminds.tv/norio-hayakawa-ufos-new-mexico-september-29-2014/30216|accessdate=October 8, 2014}}</ref> During March 1990, Norio Hayakawa lead a [[Nippon TV]] crew in [[Dulce, New Mexico]], where they interviewed the locals, including from the [[Jicarilla Apache]], tribal officials, general townsfolk, and [[ranch]]ers, about [[paranormal]] activity in the area.<ref name="YouTube 2013">{{cite web|title=Dulce, New Mexico, our first visit in 1990.....by Norio Hayakawa|website=YouTube|date=May 25, 2013|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3yWEcAdxHts|accessdate=October 8, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=DeWalton |first1=Bruce Alan |url=http://www.bibliotecapleyades.net/branton/esp_dulcebook5.htm |title=The Dulce Book |chapter=Chapter 5 "Report From A Japanese Television Crew" |accessdate=2014-10-08 }}</ref>
In the past, he has been associated with film maker and activist, [[Anthony J. Hilder]].<ref>''Literary Nevada: Writings from the Silver State'', edited by Cheryll Glotfelty - {{ISBN|978-0-87417-755-8}} - [https://books.google.com/books?id=38jx3cD6WBkC&pg=PA516&dq=%22Norio+Hayakawa%22Hilder&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwju9KLu_P7PAhUEFZQKHTxLBK4Q6AEIGzAA#v=onepage&q=%22Norio%20Hayakawa%22Hilder&f=false Page 516]</ref><ref>''UFO Digest'', November 18, 2010 [http://ufodigest.com/article/area-51-base-commander-keeps-his-cool-rare-1998-interview Area 51 base commander keeps his cool in a rare 1998 interview!!]</ref> Hayakawa and Hilder are responsible for starting the Area 51 People's Rally. The event was formed in protest against what was seen as the secrecy surrounding Area 51. In 1999 the rally kicked off on the 5th of June at the [[Little A'Le'Inn]] in [[Rachel, Nevada]]. The event began with a press conference. There were various topics discussed which included the New World and Global Government. Speakers at the event included Hilder, Ted Gunderson and Spanish speaking talk show Victor Camacho who came with a truck load of Latino listeners. The following day a gathering of about 200 people were congregating by the signs of Groom Lake Road. Demands were being made by Hilder and some others directed at the Area 51 authorities.<ref>[http://www.dreamlandresort.com/area51/1999_rally.html 1999 Peoples Rally at Area 51]</ref> Hayakawa opened the 2000 Rally. The event was covered by [[KVBC-LP|KVBC]] and [[KSNV|Channel 3 (NBC)]] with Hilder speaking to the gathering, with Joerg Arnu fielding the reporter's questions.<ref>Dreamland Resort [http://www.dreamlandresort.com/area51/2000_rally.html 2000 Peoples Rally at Area 51]</ref>
