{{Orphan|date=August 2016}}
'''Sandra Chidinma Duru-Eluobi''' is a Nigerian businesswoman and founder of Pre-Adult Affairs Organization (PAAO).
`
==Career== In business, she has been Managing Director/CEO of Sanchhy Nigeria Limited,<ref name=This>{{cite news |url=https://www.pressreader.com/nigeria/thisday/20150322/281943131373152 |title=Sandra Duru, a quiet power broker |newspaper=This Day |via=PressReader |date=22 March 2015 }}</ref> Zest Media and Entertainment, and Executives Cable and Electronics Company,<ref name=Eagle>{{cite news |author=Funsho Akinwale |url=http://theeagleonline.com.ng/imo-state-needs-to-be-rescued-duru/ |title=Imo State needs to be rescued Duru |newspaper=The Eagle |date=30 May 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160918093710/http://theeagleonline.com.ng/imo-state-needs-to-be-rescued-duru/ |archivedate=18 September 2016 }}</ref> and managed a boutique in [[Lagos]].<ref name=This/> In government, she played a role in the election of [[Rochas Okorocha]] as governor of [[Imo State]] in 2011<ref name=Guardian>{{cite news |url=https://guardian.ng/saturday-magazine/sandra-duru-bounces-back/ |title=Sandra Duru Bounces Back |newspaper=[[The Guardian (Nigeria)|The Guardian]]|date=21 March 2015 }}</ref> and has been an advisor to the Standards Organisation of Nigeria,<ref name=Guardian/> the Police Women Unit, the Police Service Commission, and Kulfana Mining Company.<ref name=Eagle/> In 2013 she considered forming her own political party and running for the state governorship herself.<ref name=Eagle/>
She is the founder of Pre-Adult Affairs Organization, an [[NGO]] recognized by the [[United Nations]]; in 2015 she announced the launch of an associated TV programme aimed at 9–35-year-olds, ''Bare It Out! With Sandra Duru''.<ref>{{cite news |author=Funsho Akinwale |url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201505252037.html |title=Nigeria: 'Bare It Out! With Sandra Duru' Kicks Off |website=All Africa |publisher=''The Guardian'' |date=23 May 2015 }}</ref> In 2014, the Nigerian Ambassador to Ivory Coast, Ifeoma Akabogu-Chinwuba, honoured her for her "contributions to providing solutions to the unemployment, violence and educational problems in Nigeria".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://encomium.ng/nigerian-ambassador-to-cote-divore-honours-chief-mrs-sandra-duru/ |title=Nigerian Ambassador to Cote d’Ivore Honours Chief (Mrs.) Sandra Duru |website=Encomium |date=16 April 2014 }}</ref> In 2016 she launched a new project, The Unity and Peace Project 2016–2020 (The Up Project).<ref name=fem>{{cite web |url=http://femininefeelings.com/breaking-dr-sandra-duru-welcomes-new-baby-dikesinachi/ |title=Breaking: Dr. Sandra Duru Eluobi Welcomes New Baby Dikesinachi |website=Feminine Feelings.com |date=13 June 2016 }}</ref>
==Personal life== In 2014 she married Emmanuel Ebuka Eulobi, a footballer;<ref name=Guardian/> their son was born in June 2016.<ref name=fem/>
